\begin{exercise}{LIM2}{Graphical Approach to Limits}{0000} 
\begin{exerciseStatement} 

Sketch the graph of a function \(f(x)\) that meets all of the following criteria. Be sure to scale your axes and label any important features of your graph.



\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
\item 

\(f(x)\) has a vertical asymptote at \(9\), but \(\lim_{x\to 9^+} f(x)\) is finite.


\item 

\(\lim_{x\to 8} f(x)=-4\), but \(f(8)=3\).


\item 

\(\lim_{x\to 6^+} f(x)=1\) but \(\lim_{x\to 6^-} f(x)\neq1\).


\end{enumerate}

     \end{exerciseStatement}
 \begin{exerciseAnswer} 

Answers vary. Here are some things to check for:



\begin{itemize}
\item Does your graph represent a function? If your graph fails the vertical line test, it is not a function. This means there are two or more points on the graph that share the same \(x\)-value, which is not allowed!
\end{itemize}



\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
\item 

The graph should have a vertical asymptote at \(x=9\). As the function approaches the vertical asymptote from the left, the function outputs should grow infinitely large in magnitude (either in the postive or negative \(y\)-direction). As the function approaches the vertical asymptote from the right, the function should bump straight into the vertical asymptote.


\item 

The graph should approach the point \((8,-4)\), but there should be a removable discontinuity (hole) in the graph right at that point (indicated by an open circle). The actual value of the function at \(x=8\) should be \(3\), so the point \((8,3)\) should be included on the graph.


\item 

There is a jump or infinite discontinuity at \(x=6\), but the function approaches the point \((6,1)\) as \(x\) approaches \(6\) from the right.


\end{enumerate}

     \end{exerciseAnswer}
 \end{exercise}

